{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 INFERNO CANTO 01}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 \ul0 \tab 1.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The first of the 14,233 lines that constitute the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2  immediately establishes a \softline
context for the poem that is both universal and particular.  It also immediately compels a reader to \softline
realize that this is a difficult text, one that may not be read passively, but must be 'interpreted.'  \softline
And the exegetical tradition that has grown upon (and sometimes over) the text is so responsive \softline
to these characteristics that it often seems to overwhelm its object.  There are so many issues \softline
raised in the poem, so many raised by its commentators, that one reads Francesco Mazzoni's \softline
extraordinarily helpful gloss to this single verse with admiration and instruction without, at first, \softline
even noticing that it is twelve pages in length (Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla \softline
"Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], pp. 14-25).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab Many commentators have pointed out that this opening verse echoes a biblical text, \softline
Isaiah's account of the words of Hezekiah, afflicted by the 'sickness unto death' (Isaiah 38:10): 'in \softline
dimidio dierum meorum vadam ad portas inferi' (in the cutting off of my days, I shall go to the \softline
gates of the nether region).  A recent commentator has suggested that Dante's view of his kinship \softline
with Hezekiah, like himself 'a model of the sinner who finds himself and redeems himself by means \softline
of repentance and hope,' was shaped by Bernard of Clairvaux, whose thoughts about Hezekiah \softline
are found in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Sermones de diversis}{\plain \fs24 \f2  III, PL 183.546-51 (see Anthony K. Cassell,  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura \softline
Dantis Americana}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 "Inferno" I}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1989], p. 13).  It \softline
is also true that many another potential 'source' has found proponents, but this one is so apposite \softline
that it has probably received more attention than any other.  One other should also be mentioned \softline
here, the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Tesoretto}{\plain \fs24 \f2  of Brunetto Latini (see note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XV.50).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab The centuries-long debate as to whether we should read the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2  as an allegory, in \softline
which the surface action is to be understood as a fictive wrapping meant to bring the reader \softline
moralizing messages, or as the 'historical' record of an actual visit to the afterworld by a specific \softline
individual begins right here.  Exemplary of the first tendency is the allegorical reading of the first \softline
verse found in Guido da Pisa (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.1): 'Per istud dimidium nostre vite accipe somnum' \softline
(for this 'middle of our life' understand 'sleep'), a reading found as well in Dante's son Pietro \softline
(Pietro1 to}{\plain \fs24 \f2  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.1), who also glosses the meaning of the line as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 somnus}{\plain \fs24 \f2  -- 'sleep' -- and thus \softline
indeed 'dream' (the related term }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 somnium}{\plain \fs24 \f2  has both meanings in Latin).  The poem, as a result, is \softline
seen as a 'dream vision,' which must be interpreted allegorically, as a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 fabula}{\plain \fs24 \f2  with a hidden \softline
meaning that needs to be teased out of it.  Mazzoni demonstrates that this basic view of the poem \softline
was common to many of its early commentators.  However, alongside of it there existed a second \softline
view (sometimes combined with the first, sometimes at least intrinsically opposing it), one which \softline
held that the reference is to the age of Dante when he made his voyage (he was thirty-five years \softline
old in 1300, half of the biblical 'three score and ten' of Psalms 89:10).  This tradition begins with \softline
his elder son (and commentator) Jacopo and reaches its clearest expression in the Ottimo's third \softline
redaction, ca. 1340 (unpublished, see Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina \softline
Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], p. 15, for the text), citing Dante's \softline
own }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (IV.xxiii.9-14) by name and chapter (and this is perhaps the first }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 precise}{\plain \fs24 \f2  textual \softline
citation of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that we possess) for the discussion of the four ages of man found there.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab These conflicting ways of looking at the narrative, present here at its very threshold, force \softline
us to make a choice as to whether we should take the poem as presenting an autobiographical \softline
narrative that, even though we know it to be fictive, must be dealt with as though it were \softline
'historical,' or as merely a fiction, and thus to be dealt with as we have been taught to deal with \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 any such human poetic production, by 'allegorizing' it to find a deeper meaning.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab Related issues are also debated by the earliest commentators, in particular the date of the \softline
vision.  While there has been disagreement even about the year of the journey to the otherworld, \softline
indicated at various points as being 1300 (e.g., }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . X.79-80, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XXI.113, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . II.98, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
XXXII.2), it is pellucidly clear that Dante has set his work in the Jubilee Year, proclaimed by \softline
Pope Boniface VIII in February of 1300.  Far more uncertainty attends the question of the actual \softline
days indicated.  Dante's descent into hell is begun either on Friday 25 March or on Friday 8 April, \softline
with the conclusion of the journey occurring almost exactly one week later.  There is a large \softline
bibliography on the question.  For a review see Bruno Basile, 'viaggio' (ED.1976.5), pp. 995-99.  \softline
Basile and this writer both find most convincing the arguments of Amerindo Camilli, "La \softline
cronologia del viaggio dantesco," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  29 (1950), 61-84, who argues strongly for the \softline
March dates.  There can hardly be a more propitious date for a beginning, as Camilli pointed out.  \softline
March 25th is, for Dante, the anniversary of the creation of Adam, of the conception and of the \softline
crucifixion of Christ, and also marks the Florentine 'New Year,' since that city measured the year \softline
from the Annunciation (25 March).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab There is a further and related problem that will detain us a moment longer.  At least since \softline
Plato's time the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 annus magnus (}{\plain \fs24 \f2 'great year'), that cycle that brings all the stars back to their \softline
original alignment in the heavens, was thought to last 36,000 years.  In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (II.v.16) Dante \softline
accepts that traditional view.  It is, however, an interesting fact that Filippo Villani, commenting \softline
on the first canto of the poem early in the fifteenth century, says that the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 annus magnus }{\plain \fs24 \f2 contains \softline
13,000 years (ed. Bellomo, p. 83).  For Villani the number does not count the years of the great \softline
revolution of the heavens, but the years of human life on earth.  His number is interesting, since it \softline
has the effect of making Dante's journey occur at nearly the precise mid-point of the cycle of the \softline
years allotted to humanity's earthly 'voyage,' a second sort of 'great year,' as it were, in the year \softline
6499 (extractable from Dante's numeration of the ages found in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . 26.118-123).  Bellomo's \softline
note to the passage in Villani suggests that there was one Christian tradition that saw the year \softline
1300 as, indeed, the midpoint in this 13,000-year cycle.  Villani's interpretation is that what is at \softline
stake here is not the story of one life but that of humanity (see Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo \softline
commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967],  pp. 18, \softline
21), for discussion of Villani's gloss, which is not acceptable in its excision of Dante's life from the \softline
equation, but has other promising aspects).  If we follow Villani, we can see that Dante's first \softline
verse, with something approaching terrifying precision, dates the opening of his poem to the \softline
midpoint of his own life and to that of the life of the species.  And thus {\u8219\'27}Nel mezzo del cammin di \softline
nostra vita{\u8219\'27} means exactly two complementary things: when the author had lived 35 of the 70 \softline
years alloted to humans; when the human race had lived the first half of its allotted time on earth.  \softline
For the most recent discussion to link a 13,000-year }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 annus magnus}{\plain \fs24 \f2  and Dante's opening verse see \softline
Guglielmo Gorni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante nella selva: il primo canto della "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Parma: Pratiche, 1995), \softline
p. 60.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 2.  mi ritrovai}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (I came to myself) has the sense of a sudden shocked discovery.  Padoan \softline
has said this well (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.2): 'It is the pained amazement of one who has only now, for \softline
the first time, become aware that he is in peril.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab The grammatical solecism ('Nel mezzo del cammin di }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 nostra}{\plain \fs24 \f2  vita / }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 mi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  ritrov}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ai}{\plain \fs24 \f2 '), mixing \softline
plural and singular first-persons, is another sign of the poet's desire to make his reader think, \softline
realizing the relation between the individual and the universal, between Dante and all humankind.  
His voyage is meant to be understood as ours as well.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva oscura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is one of the governing images of this canto and of the poem.  Many \softline
commentators point to the previous metaphorical statement found in the Dantean work that is \softline
probably nearest in time to it, the fourth treatise of his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (IV.xxiv.12), where the author \softline
refers to 'la selva erronea di questa vita' (the error-filled wood of this life).  But here the wood is \softline
to be taken 'historically' in at least a certain sense, and seems to reflect, to some readers, the \softline
condition of Eden after the Fall.  In such a reading, Dante's sinful life is as though lived in the \softline
ruins of Eden, the place to which he has let himself be led, away from the light of God.  In any \softline
case, and to agree with Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967] ), p. 85, the wood indicates not sin itself, but \softline
human life lived in the condition of sin.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 3.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   See Wisdom (Sap. 5:7): 'Lassati sumus in via iniquitate et perditionis, et ambulavimus \softline
vias difficiles; viam autem Domini ignoravimus' (We grew weary in the way of iniquity and \softline
perdition, and we walked difficult pathways; to the way of the Lord, however, we paid no \softline
attention).  The citation is found in Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . III.3).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab The word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ch{\f3\u233\'e9}}{\plain \fs24 \f2  has been a source of energetic debate.  All students of Dante understand \softline
that the accents and marks of punctuation in editions of his texts are necessarily problematic.  We \softline
have no autograph manuscript to turn to, and fourteenth-century scribal practice in this respect is \softline
various in itself and different from our own.  Here we are dealing with a dispute that has gone on \softline
for centuries (for a review see Mazzoni [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Florence: Sansoni, 1967), pp. 31-32]).  While there are a number of \softline
solutions that have been put forward, the two current views that have large numbers of supporters \softline
are that of Antonino Pagliaro (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Ulisse}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ricerche semantiche sulla "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  \softline
[Messina-Florence: D'Anna, 1967]), pp. 14-15 (n. 9), for whom }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 che}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is a 'relative conjunction' used \softline
to express mode, or result (i.e., 'so that the straight way was lost') and that of Giorgio Petrocchi \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Le Lettere, 1994 (1966)], }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , p. 3), who \softline
argues for the causal conjunction }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ch{\f3\u233\'e9}}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  We, if we were editing rather than translating the text, \softline
would side with Pagliaro (and now with Gorni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante nella selva: il primo canto della \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Parma: Pratiche, 1995], pp. 64-65). \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 5.  forte }{\plain \fs24 \f2  (dense): see Boccaccio (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.5), cited by Padoan (comm to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.5): \softline
'difficult to move through and to escape from.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 7.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Perhaps the first serious interpretive tangle for readers of the poem.  (There will be \softline
many more.)  See the summary of the various arguments presented by Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un \softline
nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), \softline
pp. 49-51.  The problem is a simple one to describe: what is the antecedent of the implicit subject \softline
of the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 {\f4 \'50}}{\plain \fs24 \f2  ('}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 It}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is so bitter...')?  There are three feminine nouns that may have that role, since the \softline
predicate adjective, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 amara}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (bitter), is also in the feminine: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 cosa}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (v. 4), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (v. 5), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 paura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (v. 6).  \softline
Mazzoni, Pagliaro (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Ulisse}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ricerche semantiche sulla "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Messina-Florence: \softline
D'Anna, 1967), p. 639, and Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ), all are \softline
convinced that }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is the antecedent.  Our translation attempts to leave the at least apparent \softline
ambiguity of Dante's phrasing intact.  On the other hand, in the role of commentator, this writer is \softline
close to certain that a sixteenth-century commentator had long ago solved the problem (and had 
many followers through the nineteenth century, e.g., Campi, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.7): the antecedent is \softline
the phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 cosa dura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Castelvetro, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.7).  Indeed, the entire passage makes good \softline
sense when read this way.  To tell of his experience in the dark and savage wood is difficult (vv. \softline
4-6) and so bitter that only dying seems more bitter; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 but}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , in order to treat of the better things he \softline
found in the wood, he }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 will}{\plain \fs24 \f2  speak.  In verse 4 it was difficult to speak of such things; in v. 9 he will \softline
speak of them (the same verb is used in each verse, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 dire}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ).  Further, the present tense of the verb in \softline
v. 7 works against }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  as antecedent: the writer is no longer in the wood.  Grammatically, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , \softline
currently the most popular choice, is the least likely of the three.  And Dante's fear (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 paura}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ), which \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 is}{\plain \fs24 \f2  present, just does not make as much logical sense as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 cosa dura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  as antecedent.  Gorni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante \softline
nella selva: il primo canto della "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Parma: Pratiche, 1995],  pp. 63-64) also believes \softline
that }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 cosa dura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is the antecedent.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 8-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   These innocent-sounding lines have been the cause of considerable puzzlement.  For \softline
a review see Mazzoni (Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 51-55.  What is 'the good' that Dante \softline
found?  What are the 'other things'?  As Parodi (cited by Mazzoni, p. 55) has argued, these terms \softline
are in antithetic relation.  This is not the usual interpretation, but perhaps a convincing one, given \softline
Dante's own earlier formulation, put in evidence by Parodi: 'lo bene e l'altro' of a person, that is, \softline
the worth and failings of a being (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  II.x.9).  See also, centuries earlier, Filippo Villani (ed. \softline
Bellomo, p. 93), 'de bonis et malis in silva repertis' (of the good and the bad found in the forest).  \softline
Following this interpretation yields the following general sense of the passage: 'Even in the depths \softline
of my sin I found God in terrible things.'  And thus the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ben}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is not here Virgil (as many \softline
commentators suggest, despite the fact that Virgil does not appear to Dante }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 in}{\plain \fs24 \f2  the forest), but, \softline
this writer would argue, God's grace in allowing Dante to learn of His goodness even in his worst \softline
experiences.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 11.  pien di sonno}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  The date is Thursday 24 March (or 7 April?) 1300.  As the text will \softline
later make clear (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XXI.112-114), we are observing the 1266th anniversary of Good Friday \softline
(which fell on 8 April in 1300, even if Dante pretty clearly also indicates 25 March as the \softline
supposed date of the beginning of the journey [see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.1]).  This would indicate that \softline
the poem actually begins on Thursday evening, the 1266th anniversary of Maundy Thursday, \softline
when the Apostles slept while Christ watched in the garden, and then even when He called to \softline
them to rise.  That this moment is recalled here seems likely: Dante, too, is 'asleep' to Christ in his \softline
descent into sin.  See Matthew 26:40-46.  This interesting observation was, as far as one can tell, \softline
first made some years ago by a student, Andrew Bramante (Dartmouth '81).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab Filippo Villani (ed. Bellomo, pp. 95-96), here thinks of the temptation by the serpent of \softline
Adam who 'quando, ratione in ipso penitus dormiente,... sensualitati factus est obediens' (when, \softline
his reason sleeping within him,... became ruled by his senses).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 13.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 colle}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (hill) is generally interpreted as signifying the good life attainable by \softline
humankind under its own powers; some, however, believe it has a supernatural meaning, e.g., \softline
Tristano Bolelli, "Il 'dilettoso monte' del I canto dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (v. 77)," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Studi in onore di Alberto \softline
Chiari}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Brescia: Paideia, 1973), pp. 165-68.  For discussion and strong support for the first \softline
reading, based in texts of Aristotle, Brunetto Latini, and Dante himself (esp. }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Mon}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . III.xvi.7: \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 beatitudo huius vitae}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [the blessedness of this life]), see Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento 
alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 58-60.  Recently \softline
Anthony Cassell has tried to make the case that this attempted climb on Dante's part is prideful \softline
and to be condemned as a sort of 'Pelagian' assault on God's grace (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura Dantis Americana}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 "Inferno" I}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1989],  pp. 22-30), a reading that has \softline
not proven particularly convincing, in part because it means that we must consider Virgil's later \softline
exhortation of Dante to climb the mountain (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.76-78) an error of considerable weight, and this \softline
seems a forced interpretation in that circumstance.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 14.  valle}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (valley): another key word in this landscape.  Dante's descent into the valley \softline
where the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is located marks a major moral failure and brings him close to death.  What all \softline
this means in terms of Dante's actual life is extremely difficult to say.  It also raises the question of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 when}{\plain \fs24 \f2  this or these misadventure(s) occurred, before March 1300, or after the imagined date of the \softline
poem's action.  This is a matter addressed centrally by Lino Pertile in "Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : Beyond \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Stilnovo}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f2  13 (1993), 47-77, if with respect to passages in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , but in ways that are relevant to the question whenever it is posed.  Does Dante \softline
restrict reference in the poem to events and activities that have occurred before 1300 (except \softline
when he develops 'prophetic' intercalations to excuse such advance knowledge)?  Or does he feel \softline
free to violate the temporal boundaries that he himself has established in order to include more of \softline
