Press, 1969, pp. 262-63): Dante's 'firm foot' is his left foot, the foot of his will, steady in its fear of \softline
the Lord; the upper right foot is his affection for God (Villani's formulation is dependent, as \softline
Bellomo points out, on that of Guido da Pisa [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.30]).  Villani concludes by \softline
