}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 32-54.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lonza}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (for the identity of this beast as hybrid born of leopard and lion see \softline
Singleton (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.32) is the first of three beasts to move against Dante as he attempts to \softline
mount the hill.  Commentators (beginning perhaps with Tommaseo [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.49-51]) \softline
frequently point to a biblical passage as lying behind Dante's three beasts, the passage in Jeremiah \softline
(Ier. 5:6) that describes three wild animals (lion, wolf, and 'pard' [a leopard or panther]) that will \softline
fall upon Jerusalemites because of their transgressions and backsliding.  The details are close \softline
enough, and the typological identification of the sinful protagonist with the backsliding Hebrews \softline
fitting enough, to make the literal sense of the situation clear.  Less positive claims may be made \softline
regarding its metaphorical valence.  For a thorough review of one of the most vexed passages in a 
canto filled with difficulty, see Gaetano Ragonese, 'fiera' (ED.1970.2), pp. 857b-861b (with \softline
extensive bibliography through 1969, if it omits the useful study of Aldo S. Bernardo ["The Three \softline
Beasts and Perspective in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Divine Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 PMLA}{\plain \fs24 \f2  78 (1963), 14-24]).  Ragonese's history of \softline
the interpretation of the three beasts includes the following details: The early commentators are \softline
strikingly in accord; for them the beasts signify }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 (1) three of the seven mortal sins: lust, pride, \softline
and avarice.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Modern interpreters mainly -- but not entirely, as we shall see -- reject this \softline
formulation.  One school cites }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.75 for the three 'sparks' that have lit evil fires in the hearts \softline
of contemporary Florentines, according to Ciacco, who is seconded by Brunetto Latini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
XV.68): }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 (2) envy, pride, and avarice}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  Others suggest that there is no reason here to believe that \softline
Dante is referring to the mortal sins}{\plain \fs24 \b\f2  }{\plain \fs24 \f2 because there is no precise textual confirmation that such was \softline
his plan.  They suggest that such a confirmation is found in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  XI.81-82, where, describing \softline
the organization of the punishment of sin, Virgil speaks of }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 (3) 'the three dispositions Heaven \softline
opposes, incontinence, malice, and mad brutishness.'}{\plain \fs24 \f2   In this approach, there are strong \softline
disagreements as to which beast represents which Aristotelian/Ciceronian category of sin: is the \softline
leopard fraud or incontinence? is the she-wolf incontinence or fraud? (the lion is seen by all those \softline
of this 'school' as violence).  For instance, some have asked, if the leopard is fraud, the worst of \softline
the three dispositions to sin, why is it the beast that troubles Dante the least of them?  A possible \softline
answer is that the scene, which takes place on earth and not in hell, is meant to show Dante's \softline
tendencies with respect to the three large areas of sin punished in hell.  If the leopard represents \softline
fraud (as its spotted hide might indicate -- it is beautiful but 'maculate' [see the argument in this \softline
vein of Padoan, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.33]), it is the disposition least present in Dante.  Perhaps the \softline
single most important passage in the text of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that identifies at least one of the three beasts \softline
in such a way as to leave no doubt occurs in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Infern}{\plain \fs24 \f2 o XVI.106-108, where Dante tells us that he \softline
was wearing a cord that he once used to attempt to capture the beast with 'the painted pelt.'  That \softline
this cord is used as a challenge to Geryon, the guardian of the pit of Fraud, makes it seem nearly \softline
necessary that in this passage the leopard is meant to signify fraud.  If that is true, it would seem \softline
also necessary that the lion would stand for Violence and the she-wolf for Incontinence.  The last \softline
formulation is the trickiest to support.  The she-wolf is mainly associated, in the poem (e.g., }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
XX.10-15), with avarice.  But avarice }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 is}{\plain \fs24 \f2  a sin of Incontinence.  Thus Dante presents himself as \softline
most firm against Fraud, less firm against Violence, and weak when confronted by Incontinence.  \softline
In his case the sin of incontinence that afflicts him most is lust, not avarice.  This is the best \softline
understanding that this reader has been able to manage.  It is not one that gathers anything like \softline
immediate consent.  The three beasts are another of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2 's little mysteries likely to remain \softline
unsolved.  But see the extended discussion in Gorni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante nella selva: il primo canto della \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Parma: Pratiche, 1995), pp. 23-55.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab The formulation of the early commentators (}{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 [1] lust, pride, and avarice}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ) has had a \softline
resurgence in our time.  It would certainly be pleasing to have reason to assent to their nearly \softline
unanimous understanding.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], pp. 99-102) has given, basing his argument on \softline
texts found in the Bible and in the writings of the Fathers and Doctors of the Church, good reason \softline
for returning to this view.  (For an opposing argument, advancing five reasons for which the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lonza}{\plain \fs24 \f2  \softline
cannot represent lust, see Romano Manescalchi [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Il prologo della "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Turin: \softline
Tirrenia, 1998)], pp. 13-36.)  If it were not for the passage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XVI.106-108, it would be easy \softline
