}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 62.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Dante's phrasing that describes Virgil's appearance to the protagonist ('dinanzi a li \softline
occhi mi si fu offerto') reminded Tommaseo (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.62) of the phrasing that describes \softline
Venus's appearance to her son, Aeneas, when the latter is intent on killing Helen in order to \softline
avenge the harm done to Troy by the Greek surprise attack within the walls of Troy: 'mihi se... \softline
ante ocul[o]s... obtulit.'  Any number of later commentators have also made this ascription.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 63.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   For lengthy reviews of the problems raised by centuries of exegesis of this difficult \softline
verse see Giorgio Brugnoli ("Chi per lungo silenzio parea fioco," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Letterature comparate: \softline
problemi e metodo.  Studi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 in onore di Ettore Paratore}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , vol. 3 [Bologna: P{\f4 \'42}tron, 1981], pp. 1169-82) and Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Il Virgilio dantesco: tragedia nella "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Olschki, 1983]), \softline
pp. 23-79.  Both of these writers independently agree on most of the key elements in the puzzle: \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 fioco}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is to be taken as visual rather than aural; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 silenzio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is understood as deriving from the \softline
Virgilian sense of the silence of the dead shades (e.g., }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.264: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 umbrae silentes}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ).  It is fair \softline
also to say that neither deals convincingly with the adjective }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lungo}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  How can one }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 see}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that a \softline
'silence' is of long duration?  A recent intervention by Gino Casagrande ("Parole di Dante: il \softline
'lungo silenzio' di }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I, 63," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Giornale storico della letteratura italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f2  174 [1997], 246-48) \softline
makes a strong case for interpreting the adjective }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lungo}{\plain \fs24 \f2  as here meaning 'vast, extensive.'  \softline
Casagrande's second point, that the 'silence' refers to the wood is well argued and seems \softline
attractive.  He believes (pp. 251-54) that Uguccione da Pisa, one of Dante's main encyclopedic \softline
sources, in the MS Can Misc. 305 in the Bodleian Library at Oxford, dating from 1262, offers the \softline
Greek word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 xylon}{\plain \fs24 \f2  as equivalent to the Latin }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lignum}{\plain \fs24 \f2  for 'forest.'  The Latin }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 silva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  may thus derive \softline
from a word that means, according to Uguccione, 'vastitas vel silentium.  Inde silva ubi sunt loca \softline
vasta et deserta et silentio plena' (vastness or silence; and thus a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 silva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is a place marked by a space \softline
that is extensive, deserted, and full of silence).  There is perhaps no other brief passage ever \softline
adduced that is as close to Dante's line.  Casagrande's paraphrase of the verse is thus 'uno che \softline
nella grande selva appariva indistinto' (one who in the vast forest was hard to make out).  This \softline
would be convincing except for a single detail: Virgil does not appear to Dante in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f2  but on \softline
the plain between forest and mountain, as the protagonist runs back down toward the forest (but \softline
not into it).  And thus one may be disposed to accept Casagrande's reading of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 lungo}{\plain \fs24 \f2  while \softline
adjusting his sense of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 silenzio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  to make it refer to the 'silent' space between the mountain and the \softline
wood.  See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I.64.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab Padoan makes the point (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.63) that it is Aristotle, and not Virgil, who is \softline
'maestro e duca de la ragione umana' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . IV.iv.8), not to mention 'maestro di color che sanno' \softline
