}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 65-66.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Dante's first spoken word as character is his own poem is Latin (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Miserere}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , 'Have \softline
mercy').  This is interesting linguistically, as it indicates a Latin capacity in the author/protagonist \softline
that might serve as a defense against those who think the poem, if it is to be taken 'seriously,' \softline
should have been written in Latin.  But the Latin in question has a more important aspect: it is the \softline
language of the Church, the first word of the fiftieth Psalm (Psalms 50:1).  Thus our hero is \softline
idenitified as a son of the Church -- albeit a currently failing one -- at the outset of the work.  For \softline
several of the recurring references to that Psalm in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , see Hollander, "Dante's Use of \softline
the Fiftieth Psalm," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f2  91 (1973), 145-50.  Vincent Truijen, 'David,' states that David \softline
is the personage in the Old Testament most referred to by Dante (ED.1970.2, p. 322b).  It has \softline
also been pointed out that, typically enough, this first utterance made by the protagonist involves \softline
a double citation, the first biblical, the second classical, Aeneas's speech to his mother, Venus \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.327-330).  See Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Princeton: Princeton \softline
University Press, 1969), pp. 88-89.  (For an earlier appreciation of the echo of Virgil's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 o dea certe}{\plain \fs24 \f2  \softline
in Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 od omo certo}{\plain \fs24 \f2  see Tommaseo, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.66.)  As for the meaning of the word \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ombra}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : the nature of shades in Dante is addressed by Domenico Consoli, 'ombra' (ED.1973.4), \softline
pp. 141-45.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 67-87.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   See Gian Carlo Alessio and Claudia Villa, "Per }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I, 67-87," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante e la \softline
"bella scola" della poesia: Autorit{\f4 \'42} e sfida poetica}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , ed. A. A. Iannucci (Ravenna: Longo, 1993 \softline
[1984], pp. 41-64), for an important consideration of Dante's debt to the traditional classical and \softline
medieval 'lives of the poets' in formulating his own brief }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 vita Virgilii}{\plain \fs24 \f2  in this passage.  Among \softline
