{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 70.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   This much-debated verse has left many in perplexity.  In what sense are we to take the \softline
phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 sub Iulio}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ?  What is the implicit subject of the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 fosse}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ?  What is the precise meaning of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 tardi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  ('late')?  Virgil was born in 70 B.C., Julius died in 44 B.C., and Virgil died in 19 B.C.  For a \softline
discussion in English see Michael Wigodsky, "'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Nacqui }{\plain \fs24 \f2 sub Iulio' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I, 70)," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f2  93 \softline
(1975), 177-83.  Hardly any two early commentators have the same opinion about this verse.  Has \softline
Dante made a mistake about the date of Julius's governance?  Or does }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 sub Iulio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  only mean 'in the \softline
days of Julius'?  Was Virgil's birth late for him to have been honored by Julius?  Or does the clause 
indicate that, although he was born late in pagan times, it was still too early for him to hear of \softline
Christianity?  The most usual contemporary reading is perhaps well stated by Padoan (comm. to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.70): the Latin phrase is only meant to indicate roughly the time of Julius, and nothing more \softline
specific than that; when Julius died, Virgil was only 26 and had not begun his poetic career, which \softline
was thus to be identified with Augustus, rather than with Julius.  Alessio and Villa ("Per }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I, \softline
67-87," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante e la "bella scola" della poesia: Autorit{\f4 \'42} e sfida poetica}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , ed. A. A. Iannucci \softline
[Ravenna: Longo, 1993 (1984)], p. 49), point out, however, that there was at least one source \softline
that would have made Dante's line make clear literal sense: a ninth-century French text of the \softline
works of Virgil with a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 vita Virgilii}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that insisted that the poet was born }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 after}{\plain \fs24 \f2  Julius had come to \softline
political power (in the triumvirate with Pompey and Crassus).  Thus it is at least possible that all \softline
the exertion of commentators is vain and that Dante is resorting to a source that makes Virgil's \softline
life run under the authority of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 both}{\plain \fs24 \f2  the first two Caesars.  (It is important for modern readers to \softline
know that Dante believed, in accord with medieval tradition, that Julius was in fact the first \softline
Roman emperor.)  For a development of this discussion, suggesting that the difficult verse has a \softline
fairly straightforward explanation, see Violetta de Angelis and Gian Carlo Alessio, "'Nacqui sub \softline
Julio, ancor che fosse tardi' (<I>Inf</I>. 1. 70)," <I>Quaderni di Acme (Facolt{\f4 \'42} de Lettere e \softline
Filosofia, Universit{\f4 \'42} degli Studi di Milano) 41 (2000), pp. 127-45.  De Angelis and Alessio point \softline
out the following. Various biographies of Virgil at least potentially available to Dante placed the \softline
Roman poet's birth in 59-58 B.C. (not in the year 70) and also told that Julius held his first \softline
consulship in Mantua in 59 B.C. Thus Virgil in these lines refers to these two facts and really \softline
means that he was born }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 sub Iulio}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , while lamenting that Caesar's death in 44 B.C., when Virgil was \softline
only fourteen or fifteen years old, deprived him of the opportunity to have been known to Caesar \softline
once he had begun writing his Eclogues, ca. 30 B.C. This seems clearly the best hypothesis that \softline
we currently have in order to explain this line.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 71.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   See Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934]), pp. 201-2, for \softline
the force and frequent presence of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 buon}{\plain \fs24 \f2  in this sense in Dante: i.e., Augustus was excellent in his \softline
role as emperor.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 73.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 poeta}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is one of the most potent words in Dante's personal vocabulary of \softline
honor and esteem.  It is used 30 times in all throughout the poem in this form, seven more times in \softline
others.  In its first use, here, it constitutes Virgil's main claim as Dante's guide.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 74.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The word }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 di}{\plain \fs24 \f2  here, as is frequently the case in Dante, means }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 da}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (from), not 'of.' \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 75.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 superbo Il{\f4 \'56}{\f3\u243\'f3}n}{\plain \fs24 \f2  clearly mirrors }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f2  III.2-3, 'superbum / Ilium.'  It almost \softline
certainly has a moralizing overtone here (see also note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.106), while in Virgil it probably \softline
only indicates the 'topless towers of Troy'; in Dante it gives us some sense that Troy may have \softline
fallen because of its }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 superbia}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , or pride.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 77.  dilettoso monte}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : in no ways different from the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 colle}{\plain \fs24 \f2  of verse 13.  See note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
I.13.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 79.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   At this first appearance of Virgil's name in Dante's text (it will appear 30 times more), \softline
it is probably worth noting that Dante's spelling of the name is not only his, but a medieval Italian 
idiosyncrasy.  Translating 'Vergilius' with 'Virgilio' was intended to lend the Latin poet a certain \softline
dignity (by associating him with the noun }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 vir}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , man) and/or a certain mysterious power (by \softline
associating him with the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 virga}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , or 'rod' with magical power).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab For Virgil as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 fons}{\plain \fs24 \f2  or 'source,' Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina \softline
Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 121, adduces Donatus's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Life of \softline
Virgil}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (cited by P{\f3\u233\'e9}zard, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante sous la pluie de feu}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Paris: Vrin, 1950], p. 352), in which Homer is \softline
said to be a 'largissimus fons' (unlimited source) of things poetic.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 81.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Why is Dante's head 'bent low in shame'?  Torraca (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.81), citing \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (IV.xxv.10), argues that the protagonist feels shame for a fault committed, his having \softline
lost the true way.  Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934], p. 202) argues, \softline
citing a passage just previous to the one adduced by Torraca (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  IV.xxv.4-5), in which \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 vergogna}{\plain \fs24 \f2  is defined as amazement in beholding wonderful things, that Dante is here expressing his \softline
dazzled admiration at the coming of Virgil, not his shame for his own fault.  That is an attractive \softline
view.  Mazzoni's treatment (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" \softline
--Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], p. 122) essentially makes room for both these \softline
interpretations.  However, a simpler solution recommends itself.  The immediate context is that of \softline
Virgil's rebuke to Dante for his failure to climb the hill and consequent ruinous flight.  It is for this \softline
reason, the argument runs, supporting Torraca's sense of the word's meaning (but not his precise \softline
interpretation), that he feels ashamed.  For a differing solution of the problem, see Andreas Heil, \softline
"Dantes Staunen und die Schaum Vergils: Bemerkungen zu }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f2  1, 61-87," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Deutsches Dante-Jahrbuch}{\plain \fs24 \f2  77 (2002), 27-43.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 84.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   For the lofty resonance of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 volume}{\plain \fs24 \f2  in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (as compared with }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 libro}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , \softline
another and lesser word for 'book') see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Princeton: \softline
Princeton University Press, 1969, pp. 78-79.  The Bible is the only other book so referred to.  \softline
Hollander continues by pointing out that two other words that usually refer to God's divine \softline
authority are also each used once to refer to Virgil or his writing: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 autore}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .I. 85) and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 scrittura}{\plain \fs24 \f2  \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.34).  For the meaning of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 cercare}{\plain \fs24 \f2  see Bellomo's note (ed. Bellomo, p. 167) to Villani's \softline
similar Latin verb (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 recircare}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ): 'studiare a fondo' (to study deeply).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 86-87.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   There has been much discussion of exactly what the 'noble style' is and where it is \softline
to be found in Dante's work.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 124-25, follows Parodi in a \softline
straightforward explanation.  The style is the 'high style' or 'tragic style' found in Virgil and other \softline
classical poets and was achieved by Dante in his odes (three of which are collected in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ), \softline
as he himself indicated in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 De vulgari Eloquentia}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (II.vi.7).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab Dante's formulation here goes further, making Virgil his sole source.  His later interactions \softline
with other poets in hell (e.g., Pier delle Vigne [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XIII], Brunetto Latini [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XV]) or relatives \softline
of poets (Cavalcante [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . X]) show that not one of them is interested in the identity of Dante's \softline
guide, a fact that reflects directly on the poems left by these three practitioners, which are \softline
markedly without sign of Virgilian influence.  Thus, not only is Virgil Dante's sole source for the \softline
'noble style,' but Dante portrays himself as Virgil's sole follower among the recent and current \softline
poets of Italy.  Perhaps more than any other claim for a literary identity, this sets him apart from \softline
them.  For the opinion that Dante's insistence on Virgil as the sole source of his poetic excelling is 
a cut at Guido Cavalcanti, see Riccardo Bacchelli "'Per te poeta fui,'" }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  42 (1965), \softline
8-9.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 88-99.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   If the hidden identities of the three beasts have caused lengthy discussion, the she-wolf, as she is presented here, has been greeted by a nearly unanimous reponse: she represents \softline
cupidity.  This sin, associated with Incontinence, is discovered in much of humankind, including \softline
Dante.  It is probably most often identified with avarice, but is related to all wrongful appetites.  It \softline
is thus the most common of sins and, because of its ready ability to infect all, the most dangerous.  \softline
See St. Paul's saying, 'Radix malorum est cupiditas' (For the love of money is the root of all evil [I \softline
Timothy 6.10]).\par
