}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 90.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 le vene e i polsi}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.90) cites Dante's previous reference to the \softline
pulses (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f2  II.4), those places where agitation of the blood is evident at the body's surface, and \softline
Boccaccio's gloss to this verse (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.90), which states that the veins and pulses tremble \softline
when blood rushes from them, a phenomenon occurring when the heart is troubled, according to \softline
Boccaccio, by fear.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 100-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   In a canto filled with passages that have called forth rivers of commentators' \softline
ink, perhaps none has resulted in so much interpretive excitement as this one.  For this writer's \softline
view, see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Princeton: Princeton University Press), pp. 89-91.  \softline
What we deal with here is the first of three (see also }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XXXIII.37-45, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XXVII.142-148) \softline
'world-historical' prophecies of the coming of a political figure (in the last two nearly certainly an \softline
emperor) who, in his advent, also looks forward to the Second Coming of Christ.  The present \softline
prophecy, insofar as Dante, as maker of prophetic utterance, wants to allow his audience to \softline
penetrate the veil, however, is of Cangrande della Scala.  That is one man's opinion.  It finds much \softline
fellowship in the late nineteenth century (e.g., Campi{\u8219\'27}s comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.101), but is opposed by \softline
most who have considered the problem in the past century (e.g., Emilio Pasquini, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dante e le \softline
figure del vero: La fabbrica della "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Milan: Bruno Mondadori, 2001), p. 163, basing \softline
his rejection on the fact that in 1300 Cangrande was a mere nineteen years old.  But see the note \softline
to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f2  XVII.76-78.  For an excellent review of the entire problem see C. T. Davis, 'veltro' \softline
(ED.1976.5), pp. 908a-912b.  The view of this reader is largely in accord with Mazzoni's (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio \softline
di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, \softline
1967]), pp. 131-33, namely, that the prophecy is insistently 'Ghibelline,' and not of a good pope or \softline
of a reform of the mendicant orders, etc.  For the view that there is indeed a Virgilian (and \softline
imperial) source for Dante's prophecy in the prediction of Augustan rule in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I (vv. 286-296) \softline
see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1969), \softline
pp. 90-91.  This view was anticipated in a discussion that has not received much attention.  The \softline
so-called 'Ottimo commento' (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.100-111) minces no words about the resonance of \softline
that Virgilian passage here.  One wonders why his observation has been so neglected.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 101.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   As for the potentially absurd but nonetheless recurring notion that the prophecy is of \softline
Dante himself, the 'poeta veltro,' it was perhaps first advanced by one Pompeo Azzolino in a letter \softline
to Gino Capponi in 1837, according to Carlo Cuini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Qualche novit{\f4 \'42} nella Divina Commedia: Il \softline
Veltro, "il gran rifiuto" ed altro}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Agugliano: Bagaloni, 1986]).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 104.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   Against those who would argue that these three 'theological' qualities move the \softline
prophecy in a religious rather than a political direction, Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento \softline
alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], pp. 133-35) \softline
responds that the attribution of such qualities to secular figures was common enough in Dante's \softline
time, and even in Dante, who says similar things about Cangrande (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . XVII.83-84).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 105.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   This 'felt' has been variously explained: the felt caps of the Dioscuri, the felt tents of \softline
the great Khan, the felt of the urns in which ballots were cast for the emperor, etc.  For a review \softline
in English see Anthony Cassell, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura Dantis Americana}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 "Inferno" I}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Philadelphia: University \softline
of Pennsylvania Press, 1989), pp. 94-113.  For still another attempt to unscramble the riddle, this \softline
time on the basis of names of parts of chivalric weaponry (e.g., OF }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 feutre}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , the outcropping from a \softline
saddle on which a charging knight rests his lance) -- see Fabrizio Franceschini ("'Tra feltro e \softline
feltro': l'interpretazione di Guido da Pisa e un gallicismo nell'italiano antico," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Scrinium \softline
Berolinense: Tilo Brandis zum 65. Geburtstag}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , vol. II, ed. P. J. Becker & others [Berlin: \softline
Staatsbibliothek-Preussischer Kulturbesitz, 2000]), p. 1023.  Those who believe that the verse \softline
refers to geographical sites in Italy and thus to the zone in which the young Cangrande would be \softline
of importance (he was only 9 years old in 1300, but was in charge of the armies of Verona only a \softline
few years later -- and before Dante first came to Verona in 1304) are few in number in the current \softline
age, but were far more numerous in the nineteenth century.  This writer is one in that camp.  The \softline
translators have, as always, respected the text of Petrocchi; their own version would read \softline
'between Feltre and Feltro.'  The strongest case against such a reading is lodged in the 'fact' that in \softline
the fourteenth century }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 nazione}{\plain \fs24 \f2  only meant 'birthplace' and not 'nation.'  Consultation of the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Grande Dizionario}{\plain \fs24 \f2  shows that this may not always be the case.  For instance, soon after Dante, \softline
Boccaccio, in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Decameron}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (II.viii.4) uses the word in its modern sense (if he perhaps \softline
significantly does }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 not}{\plain \fs24 \f2  do so in his gloss of this verse).  In addition, Latin }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 natio}{\plain \fs24 \f2  frequently also had \softline
this meaning, and Dante's noun may translate that usage (see, for example, Dante's own use of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 nationes}{\plain \fs24 \f2  at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Dve}{\plain \fs24 \f2  I.viii.4).  It is, however, true that the 'geographic' reading of the verse is a late \softline
phenomenon, perhaps beginning with the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Anonimo fiorentino}{\plain \fs24 \f2  at the very end of the fourteenth \softline
century (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.101-105).  It was repeated by John of Serravalle (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.105) \softline
only to be ridiculed by that commentator.  However, beginning with Guiniforto in 1440 (comm. to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.100-111), it gradually become the dominant understanding in the Renaissance, and is put \softline
forward by Vellutello, Daniello, and Castelvetro, all of whom believe that the prophecy refers to \softline
Cangrande.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 106.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   The phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 umile Italia}{\plain \fs24 \f2  surely recalls Virgil's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 humilem... Italiam}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . III.522-523), \softline
as has been frequently noted.  Some have argued that, in Dante, the words have a moral tint.  See \softline
Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  \softline
(Florence: Sansoni, 1967), pp. 135-36, for those, especially Parodi, who are of this opinion, \softline
mainly contending that the reference is to Italy's current lowly political condition.  In accord with \softline
this view, Mazzoni cites Dante's own similar formulations: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Epist}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . V.5: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 miseranda Ytalia}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Epist}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
VI.3: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Ytalia misera}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.76: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 serva Italia}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  Some have argued for a positive valence for the \softline
word here: see Alessandro Ronconi ("Per Dante interprete dei poeti latini," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f2  41 \softline
[1964], p. 31), who sees Italy's 'humility' as indicating her worthiness to be saved by the Veltro.\par
