}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 117}{\plain \fs24 \f2 .  The possibilities for interpreting this verse are various.  The 'second death' may refer \softline
to what the sinners are suffering now (in which case they cry out either for a cessation in their \softline
pain -- a 'death' of it -- or against their condition) or it may refer to the 'death' they will suffer at \softline
the end of time in Christ's final Judgment (in which case they may either be crying out }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 for}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that \softline
finality or }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 against}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that horrifying prospect).  Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: \softline
Sansoni, 1934]), p. 260, argues for the 'death' of the soul at the moment of damnation, rejecting \softline
the tradition in the commentaries that associates the phrasing here both with the Book of \softline
Revelation (Apoc. 20:14): the damned, at the Last Judgment, who will undergo a 'second death' \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 secunda mors}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ), and with Dante's own phrase in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Epist}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.5, which also makes the 'terror \softline
secundae mortis' the fear of the wicked Florentines of their fates at the Last Judgment.  Anna \softline
Maria Chiavacci Leonardi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inferno, con il commento di A. M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Milan: Mondadori, 1991]), \softline
p. 33, agrees with Barbi on which 'death' is at stake (the present one in hell), but not with his view \softline
that the sinners long for the 'second death,' and believes that they are lamenting its horror.  She \softline
also suggests that we hear an echo here (also adduced by Mazzoni, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Saggio di un nuovo commento \softline
alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f2  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 143, and Padoan \softline
[comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.117) of v. 31 of St. Francis's 'Laudes creaturarum' (for an earlier possible citation \softline
of that poem see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.27): 'ka la morte secunda no 'l farr{\f4 \'42} male' (the good soul, \softline
liberated by death, hopes that it will not suffer eternal damnation at the Last Judgment).  That the \softline
main supporting texts invoked by discussants all involve the Last Judgment would certainly lend \softline
support to that interpretation.  Thus one possibility is that the damned cry out for that future \softline
moment, either so that their pain will be eased (even though it will not be, since we learn it will be \softline
worse [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . VI.109-111]), or at least to put this terrible state behind them, a thoroughly \softline
comprehensible, if irrational, wish.  Another, and it is one embraced by Mazzoni, pp. 139-45, is \softline
that the sinners are crying out in fear of the punishments to come after the Last Judgment.  One \softline
can find arguments for or against this position.  It seems the most defensible (Mazzoni cites a \softline
series of texts from St. Augustine to buttress his notion that it is the Last Judgment that confronts \softline
us here).  The only potential challenge to it is that, as Umberto Bosco claims, no one has been \softline
able to find an instance of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 gridare}{\plain \fs24 \f2  that is used in this negative way (i.e., 'to cry out \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 against}{\plain \fs24 \f2 ').  And thus Bosco/Reggio (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.117) approve the judgment of Letterio \softline
Cassata, 'morte' (ED.1971.3), pp. 1040a-41b, that the damned 'invoke' the Last Judgment.  It \softline
seems to this reader that Mazzoni's solution is the most sensible, especially since, a mere two \softline
dozen lines earlier, Dante has used the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 gridare}{\plain \fs24 \f2  with exactly such a negative valence (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . \softline
I.94), when Dante is portrayed as crying out in fear because of the she-wolf.\par
