}{\plain \fs24 \f2 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f2 125.}{\plain \fs24 \f2   For Cassell's consideration of the striking word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 ribellante}{\plain \fs24 \f2 , see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura Dantis \softline
Americana}{\plain \fs24 \f2 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 "Inferno" I}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1989), pp. 77-84.  His \softline
treatment of the way in which Dante thought of Virgil (much in the way that a long Christian \softline
tradition insisted of the Hebrews) as owing his faith to the true God has the result of making \softline
Virgil guilty of turning his back on a God whom he in some ways knew.  The problem with such a \softline
formulation is that it would make Virgil's placement in Limbo problematic -- he would have had \softline
to be placed deeper in hell, for such behavior would have been an active sin against God.  \softline
Nonetheless, it is also fair to say that most commentators dodge this troublesome word.  (See, for \softline
example, Bosco/Reggio, according to whom all that is meant here is that God will not allow \softline
Virgil to enter Paradise because he was born and lived a pagan and thus had no possibility of \softline
believing in Christ to come [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f2 . I.124-126].  That is not a satisfying gloss to so strong a \softline
phrasing.)  For an attempt to find a difficult middle ground see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Il Virgilio dantesco: \softline
tragedia nella "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f2   (Florence: Olschki, 1983), pp. 145-51, and, perhaps more \softline
convincingly, Bortolo Martinelli, "Canto VII," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 Lectura Dantis Neapolitana: "Purgatorio,"}{\plain \fs24 \f2  ed. \softline
Pompeo Giannantonio (Naples: Loffredo, 1989), pp. 157-58, distinguishing }{\plain \fs24 \i\f2 rebellio lumini}{\plain \fs24 \f2  (Job \softline
24:13), an intentional and prideful act of hostility to God ('rebellion against the light') from a \softline
merely ignorant failure to have faith, as is the case with Virgil.  We should also remember that, \softline
within the fiction of the poem, this formulation is Virgil's own and may simply reflect his present \softline
sense of what he should have known when he was alive.  That is, Virgil may be exaggerating his \softline
culpability.\par
